Introduction to Functions in C

Placement: Custom functions are defined outside the int main() function because main() is itself a standard function.

Purpose: Functions are reusable blocks of code. Once defined, they can be called multiple times throughout your program to perform their designated task, reducing repetition.

Anatomy of a Function

Return Type: Specifies the type of data the function will return (e.g., int, float, char). If the function does not return any data, the void keyword is used.

Function Name: A unique identifier for the function.

Parameters/Arguments: Variables declared inside the parentheses (e.g., int a, int b) that accept input values when the function is called.

Body: The actual code enclosed in curly braces {} that executes when the function runs.

The return Keyword

Instead of printing results directly inside the function, you can use the return keyword to send a calculated value back to where the function was called.

When using return, the function's declared return type must match the data type of the value being returned (e.g., if returning a + b where both are integers, the function must be of type int).

To display a returned value, the function call itself must be wrapped in a printf statement inside main().

Function Prototypes

The Problem: The C compiler reads code line-by-line from top to bottom. If you define a function after main() and try to call it inside main(), the compiler will throw an error because it doesn't recognize the function yet.

The Solution: Use a function prototype. You declare the function's return type, name, and parameters at the very top of the script (above main()) and end it with a semicolon. This tells the compiler the function exists, allowing you to define the actual body of the function below main().
